  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering, including:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Provides guidelines for countries to implement\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigations\n\n3. The Palermo Convention\n- Focuses on preventing organized crime and money laundering\n- Signed by over 180 countries\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Sets international banking standards to prevent financial crimes\n\n5. The Egmont Group\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing between countries\n\nMost countries have their own national anti-money laundering (AML) laws that align with these international standards. Financial institutions are typically required to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
